<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-912-350  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 912 350.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Nov 20 1989 v23 n47 p15(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Supercomputer debate swirls over concerns on weapons use.andO;(supercomputer export licenses to Israel)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Booker, Ellis.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Debate is raging on the issue of what countries should be allowedto buy supercomputers from US firms in anticipation of a decisionby the Bush Administration on eight supercomputer export licensesto Israel.andP;  Some fear the supercomputers requested by severalIsraeli universities may be used for missile and nuclear weaponsresearch; recent allegations that Israel transferred sensitivemilitary technology to South Africa have intensified the fears.andO;Senator John Glenn asks that the licenses be disapproved, claimingit is unwise to provide such countries as Israel, Brazil andIndia, which have not signed the Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty,with the technology.andP;  The supercomputers involved in the licenserequests are a Convex Computer Corp C-240, a Cray Research IncX-MP/18 and X-MP/14, and IBM 3090 200S, 300S, 200E and 180Esystems, the latter two with vector facilities.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     ExportIsraelPolitical IssuesResearch and DevelopmentWeaponsColleges and UniversitiesLicensingSupercomputersComputer industry.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>